<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910705-0035</DOCNO><DOCID>910705-0035.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Bally Manufacturing Corp.:   Sale of Life Fitness Unit   To Partnership Completed</HL><DATE>07/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   BLY</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Bally Manufacturing Corp. said it completed the previouslyannounced sale of its Life Fitness computerized fitnessequipment business to a partnership that includes theoperation's management.   The financially pressed, Chicago-based operator ofcasinos, health clubs, and manufacturing facilities said thetotal consideration was about $62.5 million, &quot;subject tocertain post-closing adjustments.&quot; About $27.3 million waspaid in cash, with the remainder in the form of a new issueof the buying group's debt securities.</LP><TEXT>   Bally then exchanged 800,000 shares of its common stockand &quot;substantially all&quot; of the group's debt securities thatit received, with a holder of Bally's public debt securities.   As a result, Bally acquired approximately $48.4 million ofpublic debt securities of Bally and one of its subsidiaries.Bally used the cash portion of the purchase price to reducebank debt.</TEXT></DOC>